If you use the getter in the view, every time change detection is ran you are calling the getter.
If you work it out once in the template and store it, the getter is only used once.

Try something like the code below to help with performance.    

    @Component({
      template: `Hello {{ name }}``
    })

    class UserProfile implements OnInit {
      public user: User = new User();
      public name: string = &#39;&#39;;

      public ngOnInit(): void {
        this.name = this.user.getName();
      }
    }

Just bare in mind any logic stored in the view will be executed on every change detection (which runs a lot on standard strategy).

So even small operations can be somewhat costly. Just be sure that your component will update the value if it is changed from in the component or else where

Step 6 and 7  in this [article](https://angular-guru.com/blog/angular-performance-tips) aims to point it out, Avoid Function Calls in Views and Avoid Getters in View.

