answers.body_markdown:
by a default spring boot 2.1.x supports **spring-security-core-5.1.x** which generally generate bcrypt of $2a version

This version doesn&#39;t support BCryptPasswordEncoder with different versions. 

If you want to use other versions, you need to upgrade **spring-security-core** version

Add below in your pom.xml 

     &lt;dependency&gt;
        &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.security&lt;/groupId&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-security-core&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;5.2.0.RELEASE&lt;/version&gt;
     &lt;/dependency&gt;

then create your **BCryptPasswordEncoder** bean as below

    @Bean(name = &quot;passwordEncoder&quot;)
    	public BCryptPasswordEncoder getPasswordEncoder() {
    
    		BCryptPasswordEncoder bCryptPasswordEncoder = new BCryptPasswordEncoder(BCryptVersion.$2B);
    		return bCryptPasswordEncoder;
    
    	}

**you can pass your desired version in the constructor of BCryptPasswordEncoder.**

possible values are

&gt;  - BCryptVersion.$2A 
&gt;  - BCryptVersion.$2Y 
&gt;  - BCryptVersion.$2B

If you just return a value from function it&#39;s not cost much. You also can create getter for better syntax: 
```
get userName() {
 return this.user.getName();
}
```
but if you make some calculations in the method it can decrease render performance, but you can use [pure Pipe][1] behaviour (pure pipes implemets memorization pattern) for optimization (you can use already created [ngx-pipe-function][2].


  [1]: https://angular.io/guide/pipes#pure-and-impure-pipes
  [2]: https://www.npmjs.com/package/ngx-pipe-function

If you use the getter in the view, every time change detection is ran you are calling the getter.
If you work it out once in the template and store it, the getter is only used once.

Try something like the code below to help with performance.    

    @Component({
      template: `Hello {{ name }}``
    })

    class UserProfile implements OnInit {
      public user: User = new User();
      public name: string = &#39;&#39;;

      public ngOnInit(): void {
        this.name = this.user.getName();
      }
    }

Just bare in mind any logic stored in the view will be executed on every change detection (which runs a lot on standard strategy).

So even small operations can be somewhat costly. Just be sure that your component will update the value if it is changed from in the component or else where

Step 6 and 7  in this [article](https://angular-guru.com/blog/angular-performance-tips) aims to point it out, Avoid Function Calls in Views and Avoid Getters in View.

